  {
    "ts": "2026-03-18T08:04:45+00:00",
    "headline": "Amazon, Samsung see AI driving sales, chip demand",
    "summary": "<body><p>STORY: Amazon CEO Andy Jassy says artificial intelligence could help cloud computing unit Amazon Web Services achieve $600 billion in annual sales.</p><p>The outlook&nbsp;came in an internal all-hands meeting on Tuesday, with his comments reviewed by Reuters.&nbsp;</p><p>Jassy said with what's happening in AI, AWS has a chance to \"at least double\" his previous $300 billion revenue estimate.&nbsp;</p><p>The cloud provider booked almost $129 billion in sales in 2025, up 19% on the year.</p><p>Jassy’s projection suggests an average growth rate of nearly 17% every year for the next decade.</p><p>Wall Street has balked at Amazon's planned commitment of $200 billion in capital expenditure for AI this year, sending its shares down sharply.</p><p>But Jassy said the spending was carefully planned, and would pay off.</p><p>Samsung Electronics also sees AI continuing to drive strong demand for chips this year.</p><p>Co-CEO Jun Young-hyun said Wednesday the company expects a \"favorable business environment due to the increasing demand for AI and the resulting continued shortage of memory supply.\"</p><p>Roaring demand for semiconductors for AI data centers has curbed memory chip shipments to other sectors, allowing Samsung and rivals to sharply hike prices.&nbsp;</p><p>That has seen shares in the firm skyrocket to record highs, up around 70% since the start of the year.</p></body>",
    "url": "https://finance.yahoo.com/video/amazon-samsung-see-ai-driving-080445148.html",
    "source": "Reuters Videos",
    "provider": "yfinance",
    "raw": {
      "id": "49b07f3f-1fbe-3778-8967-0a01180a7833",
      "content": {
        "id": "49b07f3f-1fbe-3778-8967-0a01180a7833",
        "contentType": "VIDEO",
        "title": "Amazon, Samsung see AI driving sales, chip demand",
        "description": "<title><body><p>STORY: Amazon CEO Andy Jassy says artificial intelligence could help cloud computing unit Amazon Web Services achieve $600 billion in annual sales.</p><p>The outlook came in an internal all-hands meeting on Tuesday, with his comments reviewed by Reuters. </p><p>Jassy said with what's happening in AI, AWS has a chance to \"at least double\" his previous $300 billion revenue estimate. </p><p>The cloud provider booked almost $129 billion in sales in 2025, up 19% on the year.</p><p>Jassy’s projection suggests an average growth rate of nearly 17% every year for the next decade.</p><p>Wall Street has balked at Amazon's planned commitment of $200 billion in capital expenditure for AI this year, sending its shares down sharply.</p><p>But Jassy said the spending was carefully planned, and would pay off.</p><p>Samsung Electronics also sees AI continuing to drive strong demand for chips this year.</p><p>Co-CEO Jun Young-hyun said Wednesday the company expects a \"favorable business environment due to the increasing demand for AI and the resulting continued shortage of memory supply.\"</p><p>Roaring demand for semiconductors for AI data centers has curbed memory chip shipments to other sectors, allowing Samsung and rivals to sharply hike prices. </p><p>That has seen shares in the firm skyrocket to record highs, up around 70% since the start of the year.</p></body></title>",
        "summary": "<body><p>STORY: Amazon CEO Andy Jassy says artificial intelligence could help cloud computing unit Amazon Web Services achieve $600 billion in annual sales.</p><p>The outlook&nbsp;came in an internal all-hands meeting on Tuesday, with his comments reviewed by Reuters.&nbsp;</p><p>Jassy said with what's happening in AI, AWS has a chance to \"at least double\" his previous $300 billion revenue estimate.&nbsp;</p><p>The cloud provider booked almost $129 billion in sales in 2025, up 19% on the year.</p><p>Jassy’s projection suggests an average growth rate of nearly 17% every year for the next decade.</p><p>Wall Street has balked at Amazon's planned commitment of $200 billion in capital expenditure for AI this year, sending its shares down sharply.</p><p>But Jassy said the spending was carefully planned, and would pay off.</p><p>Samsung Electronics also sees AI continuing to drive strong demand for chips this year.</p><p>Co-CEO Jun Young-hyun said Wednesday the company expects a \"favorable business environment due to the increasing demand for AI and the resulting continued shortage of memory supply.\"</p><p>Roaring demand for semiconductors for AI data centers has curbed memory chip shipments to other sectors, allowing Samsung and rivals to sharply hike prices.&nbsp;</p><p>That has seen shares in the firm skyrocket to record highs, up around 70% since the start of the year.</p></body>",
